In contrast, Idea 1 (GASLE) introduces a fundamentally new dimension: **geometric awareness via directional operators learned from handwriting dynamics**, encoded directly into the Latinized sequence. This goes beyond both StrokeNet and HNLSR by embedding *spatial topology* and *relative positioning* through differentiable modeling of stroke transitions (DSPM) and Geometry-Aware Self-Attention (GASA). No existing paper addresses spatial relationships between strokes in a learnable, sequence-compatible format. Papers 1 and 3 use visual or graph structures, but they do not translate geometric relationships into an augmented Latin string that remains compatible with standard subword tokenizers. GASLE’s use of directional operators (→, ⊂, etc.) as part of the input sequence enables both interpretability and model sensitivity to layout—something absent in all cited works. Furthermore, MorphoAugment techniques like Mirror Perturbation operate on geometric logic, introducing a new class of augmentations not seen in prior art.

Thus, while both ideas are highly novel, **Idea 1 (GASLE)** demonstrates a clearer departure from existing literature by unifying temporal stroke order, spatial geometry, and directional semantics within a Latin-compatible framework—offering a new axis of generalization for logographic NMT. Its methodological innovation in encoding spatial reasoning into discrete sequences with neural-grounded operators represents a significant and underexplored direction.

